e of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vergy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Herefordshire): nickname from Middle English <i>verrei</i>, <i>verie</i> ‘true; reliable, trustworthy’ (Old French <i>verai</i>).","Irish: variant of <b>McVerry</b>, a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fearadhaigh</b>, itself an unlenited and subsequently voiced variant of <b>Mac Fhearadhaigh</b>, ‘son of <i>Fearadhach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘manly’. Compare   McAree   and   McCary  ; also the surnames   Ferry   and   Farry  , from <i>Ó Fearadhaigh</i>.","History: The widow Bridget Very settled with her children in Salem, MA, <i>c.</i> 1634. She had many prominent descendants, including the poet Jones Very (1813–1880)."],"variants":[{"name":"McAree","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhearadhaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Fearadhach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘manly’ (from <i>fear</i> ‘man’). Pronunciation of this name as <i>McAree</i> led to misinterpretation as <i>Mac an Rí</i> ‘son of the king’ and thus to ‘translation’ as   King  . See   McGarry  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugues","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Hugues Capet  (  ?938–96 ) was ruler of France (  987–96 ) and founder of the Capetian dynasty.  See  <b>Hugh</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugues de Vergy was born about 1210, in Mirebeau, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France, his father, Guillaume De Vergy I, was 31 and his mother, Clémence de Fouvent, was 22. He had at least 1 daughter. He was buried in Cherlieu, Isère, Rhône-Alpes, France."},"et":{"ABT 1210–":"umbes 1210–Surnud","1207–1268":"1207–1268","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1214–Female":"1214–Surnud","1215–1263":"1215–1263","1215–1278":"1215–1278","1218–Male":"1218–Surnud","1235–1286":"1235–1286","1180–1240":"1180–1240","1190–1263":"1190–1263","1190":